Important To Point Out One can speak of the structure of the long term structure of the solar system.
The whole object of developing a theory for the way planetary systems form is that they meet the
following criterion: They predict the Titius-Bode rule for the distribution of the planets; the distribution
gives the planetary orbital periods from Newton’s Universal Law of Gravitation. The distribution of the
planets is chieﬂy predicted by three factors: The inward forces of gravity from the parent star, the outward
pressure gradient from the stellar production of radiation, and the outward inertial forces as a cloud
collapses into a ﬂat disc around the central star. These forces separate the ﬂat disc into rings,
agglomerations of material, each ring from which a different planet forms at its central distance from the
star (they have widths). In a theory of planetary formation from a primordial disc, it should predict the
Titius-Bode rule for the distribution of planets today, which was the distribution of the rings from which
the planets formed.

The unit of a second becomes important in my theory. We got the second from the rotation period of the

That is as the Earth’s day gets longer and the lunar orbit grows larger, we got the second at the time that
the Earth day was what it is during the epoch when the Moon perfectly eclipses the Sun, 24 hours.

Introduction
Here I present the basics of a rudimentary theory of everything and explore the archaeological question it
asks, which is whether something from outside, like extraterrestrials, or an ancient lost civilization,
inﬂuenced the development of the mathematics we have today. The theory of everything is like an analog
for the solution of the Schrödinger equation solution of the hydrogen atom in quantum mechanics but for
the Solar System. As well it predicts the radius of a proton. As such it shows a connection between the
macrocosmos and the microcosmos. This connection comes about through a characteristic time of 1
second. Since the second came to us from the ancient Sumerians with their base 60 counting, the
archaeological question of where did the second come from and can it be found in ancient stone
observatories, or megalithic sites in general, and in the Egyptian pyramids, arises. We ﬁnd it can be
thought to, and to these ends we look at theories concerning European megalithic stone circles, ancient
Egyptian pyramids, and the extraordinary site is Turkey (Gobekli Tepe), fairly recently unearthed, which
pushes things back 6000 years into the end of the last ice age. To tie things together we suggest the
possibility of an outside inﬂuence on the development of our mathematics that could be from Graham
Hancock’s controversial Lost Ice Age Civilization, or from extraterrestrial contact in ancient times.

It is at this point that we have to ask: Did extraterrestrials give the Sumerians writing and the sciences,
and indeed metallurgy? Mysteriously, the Sumerians seemed to make the transition to this from hunting,
following the herds, and crafting stones into spearpoint, overnight on an archaeological timescale. Or, is it
that their mathematics optimized our modern physics because their choice of base 12 and base 60 for their
counting was wise in the sense that these numbers have a powerful dynamic behind them that Nature
utilizes? There is a third possibility, and that is that there was an ice age civilization that was advanced,
but mostly destroyed by a cataclysm, and their survivors traveled into the world to reboot civilization.
Traveling ultimately to ancient Egypt, and Sumer. Both these places started civilization at about the same
time which could explain this. This is the theory put forward by Graham Hancock for a lost ice age
civilization that was destroyed by a meteor impact in North America, melting ice sheets during the
Younger Dryas 12,900 years ago that caused massive ﬂoods which are the source of the ﬂood myths in
many cultures. Hancock argues that survivors of this catastrophe passed down knowledge to later cultures
like Egyptians, Maya, and Mesopotamians who all have similar megalithic architecture and myths.
Archaeology can be rewritten. The date for which Native Americans came to the New World keeps
getting pushed back. Gobekli Tepe was systematically excavated in 1995 by Klaus Schmidt in South
Eastern Turkey. Only about 5% of the site has been excavated, but it is a megalithic site with T-shaped
stone pillars with carvings on them, much of animals, but so far no writing. This site puts back the time
that humans built megalithic sites by 6,000 years. What’s more it was built by hunter gatherers and before
its discovery it was believed only post ice-age agricultural civilizations built megalithic sites. It predates
Stonehenge and the Egyptian pyramids by 7,000 years.
Hancock argues that the sophistication of the architecture, precise astronomical alignments, and intricate
carvings of Gobekli Tepe suggest it was built by a people with advanced knowledge, that may have arisen
from a now-lost civilization. That it was not the beginning of civilization, but the recovery of civilization.

Alexander Thom (1894-1985) was a Scottish engineer educated at Oxford. Trained as a mechanical
engineer he became interested in megalithic sites and conducted extensive surveys of stone circles for
sites across Britain and France.
He proposed that Neolithic builders of the ancient stone sites in Europe, such as Stonehenge, that aligned
with celestial periods and patterns in the sky used a standardized unit of measurement, which he called the
megalithic yard (MY) which he found to be 2.72 feet or about 0.829 meters. He found that recurrent
throughout the spacing of stones in these ancient, stone observatories was 2.5 megalithic yards. The same
2.5 that equals the 60/24 of ancient Sumerian mathematics that is in our equations for a theory of
everything.
His methods used circular and elliptical geometry to show rough rings were actually designed shapes.
Although his megalithic yard is not universally accepted, his work laid the foundations in archaeology to
quantify patterns rather than rely on qualitative descriptions and to use statistics to determine whether
something was intentional or coincidental. Today archaeoastronomy is a recognized ﬁeld, partly thanks to
his archaeological work on these ancient observatories.
Christopher Dunn is an aerospace engineer with decades of experience in precision manufacturing, laser
technology, and advanced engineering. His technical background greatly inﬂuenced his analysis of the
Great Pyramid of Giza, which lead him to propose that the Giza pyramid was not a tomb, but a
sophisticated machine harnessing energy, acoustics, and harmonic resonance. Mummy’s or burial artifacts
were never found in the King’s Chamber.
He suggests the Giza pyramid was a microwave generator or a resonant energy device. He said it was not
a tomb because it has engineering features too precise and advanced for a tomb. It is known today that the
pyramid’s near-perfect alignment, seamless stone ﬁtting, and mathematical precision (it incorporates pi
and the golden ratio) suggest knowledge beyond what is attributed to the Bronze Age.
His idea was as follows: The Queen Chamber’s shafts—which were thought to be for ventilation, and ran
through the pyramid—were too precisely engineered to be for that. Rather, they mixed chemicals, like
zinc + hydrochloric acid to produce hydrogen gas, which ﬂowed upward. Hydrogen entered the King’s
Chamber, where sound waves from Earth’s vibrations or ritual chants excited the gas, creating standing
waves. The chambers granite rich in quartz converted mechanical energy (piezoelectric conversion) from
vibrations into microwave electromagnetic energy. Microwaves were funneled through the pyramid’s
shafts, focused by its shape, to obelisks that were used as receivers/transmitters for wireless power.
